label.string: What does my formaldehyde level mean?

fragment.content: The exact healthy levels for indoor formaldehyde isn’t set.

fragment.string: • 8 ppb for indoor at home (Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry (ATSDR) chronic minimum risk level) • 40 ppb for indoor at home over 8 hours (Health Canada's Residential Indoor Air Quality Guideline for 8 hours) • 16 ppb for workplace over 8 hours (NIOSH Recommended Exposure Limit (REL) for 8 hours) • 750 ppb (500 ppb action level) for workplace danger limit: (OSHA workplace limit)

Here are two ways to cut down indoor formaldehyde levels:
STEP 1 Remove or stop the source. Common sources include:

• Smoking • Pressed wood products (plywood/particleboard) • Adhesives used in new carpet • Certain types of new hardwood flooring • Gas stove • Other gas appliances • Use of nail polish • Use of adhesives/glues • Use of paints • New indoor paint • All-purpose cleaner (certain types) • Window cleaner (certain types)

• Not smoking indoors • Removing pressed wood products (plywood/particleboard) • When possible, go outdoors if you must use paints/adhesives/glues/nail polish • Using a vent fan with gas appliances • Using no-VOC or low-VOC indoor paint • Changing to natural cleaning products or soap and water
This only applies if the outdoor air has low formaldehyde concentrations, which it does in most cases.
• Open windows (this works best by opening windows on two sides of the house for a cross-breeze) • Window fans (drawing outdoor air into the house)

• Home air filters and purifiers - Activated carbon filters are the best for removing formaldehyde, but they may not work for long because they get saturated quickly. Otherwise, home air filters and purifiers don’t usually work well on changing indoor formaldehyde levels.
Household plants can also improve overall indoor air quality, but their ability to reduce formaldehyde is likely very small.

Formaldehyde can cause irritation to the skin and lining of the eyes, nose, mouth, throat, and airways. This irritation might worsen the symptoms for people with conditions like respiratory diseases and allergies. Being around higher levels of formaldehyde for long periods of time has also been linked to some cancers.

fragment.content: More information can be found at www.epa.gov/formaldehyde

label.text: Take a survey about your health

label.string:
Summary: The purpose of this research project is to design a smartphone app to allow community scientists to determine atmospheric formaldehyde concentrations in their homes or in outdoor air. We would like to receive feedback from you about your experience using the app in this beta test. Your participation is voluntary and all questions are voluntary. Contributing your data will help us make sure that this app meets your needs and is as easy to use as possible.
The purpose of this research project is to design a smartphone app to read color-changing badges and report formaldehyde concentrations for community scientists. We would like to receive feedback from you about your experience using the app in this beta test. The research is being conducted by Ohio State University in conjunction with the Public Laboratory for Open Technology and Science (Public Lab). Insights from community scientists and other relevant members of the public is key to developing the most robust and useable technology possible. You are invited to participate in this research project because you have expressed interest in measuring formaldehyde using this app.
Your participation in this research study is voluntary. You may choose not to participate in the research component and can still use the app for personal use. If you decide to participate in this research survey, you may withdraw at any time. If you decide not to participate in this study or if you withdraw from participating at any time, there will be no penalty or loss of benefits that participants are entitled to. You may skip any questions you do not wish to answer. If you want do not wish to complete this survey just close your browser.
The procedure involves filling an online survey that will take approximately 10 minutes. Your responses will be confidential and we do not collect identifying information such as your name, email address, IP address or GPS location. The survey questions will be about your interest in testing for airborne formaldehyde, how we should build the software and hardware for this technology to best suit your needs, and reflections on past community science studies (if applicable).
We will work to make sure that no one sees your survey responses without approval. But, because we are using the Internet, there is a chance that someone could access your online responses without permission. In some cases, this information could be used to identify you. We will do our best to keep your information confidential. All data is stored in a password protected electronic format. To help protect your confidentiality, the surveys will not ask for information that will personally identify you. The results of this study will be used for scholarly, technical development, public education purposes, or community-science inquiry.
For questions, concerns, or complaints about the study, or you feel you have been harmed as a result of study participation, you may contact Karen Dannemiller at 614-292-4031.
For questions about your rights as a participant in this study or to discuss other study-related concerns or complaints with someone who is not part of the research team, you may contact Ms. Sandra Meadows in the Office of Responsible Research Practices at 1-800-678-6251.This research has been reviewed according to Ohio State University IRB procedures for research involving human subjects.
Please print a copy of this consent form for your records, if you so desire.

label.string: This optional survey will ask you about your current health information. It can be completed prior to measuring formaldehyde in your home and should be completed only once. Your SmART-Form ID can link your later formaldehyde reading to this survey without linking it back to you. The survey is completed in an external browser through Qualtrics.
